<table  border=0 cellpadding=2 cellspacing=0 awidth=100%><a name=99601412425378></a><form action=http://eqdb.allakhazam.com/strategy/mrate.pl name=f99601412425378><tr><td id=headerrow><span id=sj><a href=/strategy/classes.html?class=3&mid=99601412425378>RE: What are monks good for.</a></span></td><td align=right id=headerrow valign=bottom><span id=notbold>By:</span> <a href=poster.html?id=67705><span id=Sage>Kensuke</span></a>, <span id=Sage>Sage</span><br><span id=notbold>72 posts</td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 id=headerrow>Posted @ Tue, Jul 24th 6:35 PM 2001</td>
	   <td id=headerrow align=right><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Good<span id=notbold>[3.70]</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=2>Hmm... each class has their definite advantages over eachother. <br><br>Monks, though, are good for several things. One is that they're among the best pullers once they learn Feign Death and become proficient in the skill, and the art of feign splitting. <br><br>Feign death is also one of the best skills in the game. You rarely ever have to worry about dying, and if you do die, it's usually because of a stroke of bad luck. (I do believe, though, that the coding was recently changed on FD by Verant that makes it less reliable... not sure if this is true) <br><br>They're very self-sufficient, able to heal 25% of their hitpoints every six minutes. Combine this with Bind Wound, and they can restore their health up to 75% on their own, and later in life, when monks can bind up to 75% health, they can completely restore their health without the aid of others. <br><br>Monks are also very low maintenance. We don't have to concern ourselves with dozens of different armors and weapons. There aren't many monk weapons and monk armors, but what's out there can last us a very long time. <br><br>Monks can also deal out the most damage the fastest out of the pure melee classes. <br><br>Compare this to the advantages of the rogue class, and come to your own conclusion. <br><br>Personally, I have a rogue, and I enjoy playing my monk far more then I do the rogue. <br>&nbsp;<br> </td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 >&nbsp;</td><td align=right valign=bottom>
	   <span style='font-weight: normal; font-size: 9px;'>[<a href=#top>Top</a>]</span></tr>
	   </form></table><ul>
<table  border=0 cellpadding=2 cellspacing=0 awidth=100%><a name=99605318641760></a><form action=http://eqdb.allakhazam.com/strategy/mrate.pl name=f99605318641760><tr><td id=headerrow><span id=sj><a href=/strategy/classes.html?class=3&mid=99605318641760>RE: What are monks good for.</a></span></td><td align=right id=headerrow valign=bottom><span id=notbold>By:</span> <a href=poster.html?id=57570><span id=Scholar>Niteklaw</span></a>, <span id=Scholar>Scholar</span><br><span id=notbold>49 posts</td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 id=headerrow>Posted @ Wed, Jul 25th 5:26 AM 2001</td>
	   <td id=headerrow align=right><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Excellent<span id=notbold>[4.65]</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=2>I'll take "The other aproach", and tell you about what's FUN and what's NOT about the monks. (Not fun could also be called "Limitations" instead. Semantics...)<br><br>FUN:<br>1) Looooots of damage dealt. No-one can open a can of Whoop-Ass like a monk.<br>2) Group if you like, solo if you like. You will never find yourself utterly dependant on others.<br>3) Versatility. Monks have many nice skills that make adventuring easier (Safe Fall, Sneak - which Rogues also have, so what's my point?)<br>4) Feign Death! What can I say? Other than being a nice tool for pulling, this skill outperforms any Gate, Evac, SoW, "Mesmerize-and-Flee-in-Terror" in the game as far as saving your life. Go ahead and Solo that Yellow Con if you like. You can always just abort (Ofcourse, later on the MoBs will start noticing that you weren't dead after all and come back for you).<br>5) Did I mention that Monks can kick butt like nobody's busines?<br>6) Getting Agro'ed on the occasional Corpse Run? Even a "Naked" monk can turn around and stop any oportinist MoB dead in his tracks.<br>7) I can't explain why, but monks are somehow rather "Cool".<br>8) Ouchie! Monks can really hurt people.<br><br>Not so much Fun:<br>1) Weight limits. If you are often going for D4 Ph4T L3wt, don't pick a monk. Loot one single heavy item and you'll have to run back to town before you can fight effectively again. You will also often see monks having to dump money everywhere too. Always painful.<br>2) You're a fighter, but so much nice fighter-equipment cannot be used by monks.<br>3) Monks are 100% offense, so don't think you can take all that much punishment. At higher levels you might often need another tank to taunt the MoBs away from you, and this can be difficult because of the massive damage you are dealing.<br>4) When in a group, YOU will always be picked as the primary puller. Expect to be running around looking for targets and splitting them while the others sit back, meditate, and talk about life's little mysteries.<br>5) Monks get some truly amazing equipment, but often have to make an amazing effort to obtain it.<br><br>But when all is said and done, the Monk is the most fun for me, and I've tried quite a few other things. (Necro, Chanter, Shadow Knight, Warrior, Cleric, Ranger, Rogue, well most classes, really).<br><br>Incidently, i DO envy the Rogues' ability to measure damage in KHP (Kilo-Hit Points), but hits like these are rare, and only under certain conditions. In a normal Man-to-Man fight, a monk generally deals more damage over time.<br><br>Niteklaw "Lean Green Fighting Machine" Ahzi'Dahaka<br>Iksar Monk with a high opinion of himself<br>Povar-Tarew Artisans, Xev.<br>&nbsp;<br> </td></tr>
